'''Rio Chima Ngumoha''' (born 29 August 2008) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left winger]] or [[attacking midfielder]] for {{English football updater|Liverpoo}} club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].

== Club career ==
=== Chelsea ===
Ngumoha joined the [[Chelsea F.C. Development Squad and Academy|Chelsea academy]] aged eight and scored in Chelsea's 3–1 win over Wolves in the [[Premier League Cup (football)|U17 Premier League Cup]] final in April 2024.<ref>{{cite web|website=Talksport|url=https://talksport.com/football/2402643/rio-ngumoha-liverpool-southampton-ballon-dor-raheem-sterling|title= Rio Ngumoha believes he can achieve 23-year Liverpool Ballon d'Or feat after Raheem Sterling tip|accessdate=19 December 2024|first=Joe|last=Brophy|date=18 December 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Morgan | first1=Rich | last2=Bitibiri | first2=Will | title=Rio Ngumoha: Who is 16-year-old Liverpool winger and how did he break into Arne Slot&#039;s first-team squad? | website=Sky Sports | date=5 August 2025 | url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13407507/rio-ngumoha-who-is-16-year-old-liverpool-winger-and-how-did-he-break-into-arne-slots-first-team-squad | access-date=26 August 2025}}</ref>

=== Liverpool ===
Ngumoha joined [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the summer of 2024 which reportedly led to a worsening of relations between the two clubs due to the nature of his exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/who-rio-ngumoha-chelsea-wonderkid-29519929.amp|website=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=14 September 2024|title= Who is Rio Ngumoha? Liverpool wonderkid 'worth £60m' signed from Chelsea|first1=Amie|last1=Wilson|first2=Tom|last2=Cavilla|date=5 September 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-plan-rio-ngumoha-new-29932754.amp |website=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=14 September 2024|title= Liverpool plan for Rio Ngumoha as new signing finally ready for debut before Milan trip |first=Ian|last=Doyle|date=14 September 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5628841/2024/07/10/liverpool-rio-ngumoha-transfer-chelsea/|url-access=subscription|title=Liverpool set to sign Rio Ngumoha, 15, from Chelsea|first=James|last=Pearce|website=The Athletic|date=10 July 2024|accessdate=14 September 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Liverpool news: When Rio Ngumoha's exit upset Chelsea|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/crev4nj087eo|website=BBC Sport|date=26 August 2025|access-date=30 January 2026|language=en-GB|first=Nizaar|last=Kinsella}}</ref> On 5 February 2026, a Professional Football Compensation Committee (PFCC) tribunal ordered that Liverpool must reimburse Chelsea a minimum of  £2.8 million for Ngumoha's training and development while with the Blues.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Adam |title=Liverpool to pay Chelsea at least £2.8m for Ngumoha |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c1dkvy56vn3o |access-date=6 February 2026 |work=BBC Sport |date=5 February 2026}}</ref>

In the autumn of the [[2024–25 Liverpool F.C. season|2024–25 season]], Ngumoha was called-up to train with the Liverpool first team squad by manager [[Arne Slot]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-handed-welcome-sight-talented-30331511.amp|website=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=18 December 2024|title=Liverpool handed welcome sight as talented player makes return to Arne Slot training session|first=James|last=Quinlan|date=8 November 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=empireofthekop|url=https://www.empireofthekop.com/2024/11/23/rio-ngumoha-liverpool-training/|accessdate=18 December 2024|title=Presence of teenage academy starlet in Liverpool training suggests Arne Slot adoration|date=20 November 2024|first=Peter Kenny |last=Jones}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribuna.com/amp/en/news/liverpoolfc-2024-12-10-rio-ngumoha-impresses-in-training-but-misses-out-on-girona-clash-due-to-uefa-rules/|website=Tribuna.com|accessdate=18 December 2024|title= After impressing in training, Rio Ngumoha misses out on Girona clash due to UEFA rules|date=13 December 2024}}</ref> He was named amongst the match day substitutes for Liverpool's [[2024–25 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] tie against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on 18 December 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2024/12/who-is-rio-ngumoha-16-year-old-winger-named-in-liverpools-first-team/|title= Who is Rio Ngumoha? 16-year-old winger named in Liverpool's first team|date=18 December 2024|website=This is Anfield|accessdate=18 December 2024|first=Jack|last=Lusby}}</ref> On 11 January 2025, Ngumoha made his professional debut as a [[Starting lineup|starter]] in Liverpool's 4–0 win against [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in the [[2024–25 FA Cup|FA Cup]]. He became the youngest Liverpool player to appear in the FA Cup aged 16 years, 135 days and at the same time became the youngest player to start a first-team game in the club's history,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/rio-ngumoha-becomes-liverpools-second-youngest-debutant?amp=1 |website=Liverpool FC|accessdate=17 January 2025|title= Rio Ngumoha becomes Liverpool's second-youngest debutant|first=Chris|last=Shaw|date=12 January 2025}}</ref> before being substituted off for [[Jayden Danns]] in the 71st-minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2025/01/who-is-rio-ngumoha-liverpools-surprise-16-year-old-starter-in-fa-cup/|title=Who is Rio Ngumoha? Liverpool's surprise 16-year-old starter in FA Cup|date=11 January 2025|website=This is Anfield|accessdate=11 January 2025|first=Jack|last=Lusby}}</ref>

Ngumoha was included in the Liverpool squad for the July 2025 [[2025–26 Liverpool F.C. season|pre-season]] tour to [[Hong Kong]] and [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/liverpool-name-29-man-squad-pre-season-tour-asia|title=Liverpool 29-man squad for pre-season tour to Hong Kong and Japan.|date=20 July 2025|work=Liverpoolfc.com|accessdate=31 July 2025}}</ref> He featured for the club in pre-season friendlies, being praised for his performances, getting two goals and two assists across his four games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c4gmevn5ye0o|title=Rio Ngumoha raises first-team hype with Liverpool goal at Anfield|date=4 August 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 25 August, Ngumoha made his Premier League debut as an added-time substitute for [[Cody Gakpo]] and scored in the 10th minute of stoppage time, securing a 3–2 away win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and becoming the [[List of Liverpool F.C. records and statistics#Goalscorers|youngest goalscorer in club history]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=25 August 2025 |title=Newcastle vs Liverpool |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c776m8l58j8t#Report |access-date=25 August 2025 |work=[[BBC News]] |department=[[BBC Sport]] |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=25 August 2025 |title=Rio Ngumoha's 100th-minute winner gives Liverpool thrilling 3-2 win at Newcastle |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/rio-ngumohas-100th-minute-winner-gives-liverpool-thrilling-3-2-win-newcastle |access-date=25 August 2025 |website=[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]}}</ref> The goal also surpassed [[Darwin Núñez]]'s winning goal against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in March 2024 by a minute to become the club's latest game-winning goal in the Premier League.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shaw |first=Chris |date=25 August 2025 |title=Rio Ngumoha strike is Liverpool's latest ever Premier League winner |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/rio-ngumoha-strike-liverpools-latest-ever-premier-league-winner |access-date=26 August 2025 |website=[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]}}</ref> On 17 September, a month later, he made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut in a 3–2 victory over [[Atlético Madrid]], at just 17 years and 19 days old, making him the youngest Liverpool player to appear in the competition, breaking the previous record held by [[Trey Nyoni]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/rio-ngumoha-makes-history-liverpools-youngest-appearance-maker-europe |title=Rio Ngumoha makes history as Liverpool's youngest appearance-maker in Europe |publisher=Liverpool FC |date=17 September 2025 }}</ref> A week later, on 25 September, he signed his first professional contract with Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/rio-ngumoha-signs-first-professional-contract-liverpool-fc |title=Rio Ngumoha signs first professional contract with Liverpool FC |publisher=Liverpool FC |date=25 September 2025 }}</ref> 

On 11 April 2026, Ngumoha scored his first goal at [[Anfield]] in a 2–0 win against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], becoming the youngest player to achieve this feat, aged 17 years and 225 days, breaking the previous record set by [[Raheem Sterling]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hunter |first1=Andy |title=Rio Ngumoha sparks Liverpool win over wasteful Fulham with first Anfield goal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2026/apr/11/liverpool-fulham-premier-league-match-report |website=The Guardian |access-date=11 April 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Dickinson |first=Adam |url=https://www.tntsports.co.uk/football/premier-league/2025-2026/rio-ngumoha-liverpool-fulham-andy-robertson-youngest-goalscorer-anfield_sto23289547/story.shtml |title=Liverpool’s Rio Ngumoha ignored Andy Robertson’s ‘screams’ and made Premier League history at Anfield - ‘He was unbelievable’ |publisher=TNT Sports |date=11 April 2026 }}</ref>

== International career ==
Born in England, Ngumoha is of [[British Nigerians|Nigerian]] and [[Guadeloupe|Guadeloupean]] descent. Rio holds both Nigerian and French nationalities from his parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballinnigeria.com.ng/news/transfer-news/rio-ngumoha-makes-historic-liverpool-debut-after-leaving-chelsea/|title=Rio Ngumoha Makes Historic Liverpool Debut After Leaving Chelsea - Football In Nigeria|first=Kelechi|last=Abel|date=12 January 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Silas |first=Don |date=4 September 2024|title='My mother is from France' - Rio on why he snubbed France, Nigeria |url=https://dailypost.ng/2024/09/04/my-mother-is-from-france-rio-on-why-he-snubbed-nigeria-france/ |location=Lagos, Nigeria|access-date=5 September 2024 |newspaper=[[Daily Post (Nigeria)|Daily Post]]|language=en-US |archive-date=10 September 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240910113312/https://dailypost.ng/2024/09/04/my-mother-is-from-france-rio-on-why-he-snubbed-nigeria-france/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his England under-15 and [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] debuts in 2023.<ref name="Soccerway"/> In October 2024, he played for [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]].<ref>{{cite web |title=England MU17s squad named for October qualifiers|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2024/oct/18/england-mens-under-17s-squad-announcement-october-20241810|publisher=England Football|date=18 October 2024|access-date=11 January 2025}}</ref> He was called-up for the [[2025 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]].<ref name="baker">{{cite web|website=Goal|url= https://www.goal.com/en-gb/lists/max-dowman-rio-ngumoha-future-england-stars-watch-under-17-european-championship/blt758f1247b2955a7e#cs2b72fdc2f70a0f43 |first= Tom |last=Maston|date=19 May 2025|title=Max Dowman, Rio Ngumoha and six future England stars to watch at the Under-17 European Championship|accessdate=19 May 2025}}</ref>

On 3 September 2025, Ngumoha made his [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] debut during a 2–0 win over [[Ukraine national under-19 football team|Ukraine]] at the [[Pinatar Arena]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2025/Sep/03/england-mens-under-19s-ukraine-match-report-20250309|website=EnglandFootball.com|accessdate=5 September 2025|date=3 September 2025|title= Report: England MU19s 2-0 Ukraine|first=Nicholas|last=Veevers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=Liverpool FC|date=3 September 2025|last1=Williams|first1=Sam|title= Rio Ngumoha makes England U19s debut|url= https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/rio-ngumoha-makes-england-u19s-debut|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20250903145001/https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/rio-ngumoha-makes-england-u19s-debut|archive-date=3 September 2025}}</ref>

On 23 May 2026, it was announced Ngumoha was one of four players (alongside [[Alex Scott (footballer, born 2003)|Alex Scott]], [[Josh King (footballer, born 2007)|Josh King]] and [[Ethan Nwaneri]]) that would join the [[England national football team|senior team]] for the squad's preparation camp before the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Young England talents to join Three Lions in Florida |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2026/May/22/young-england-talents-to-join-three-lions-in-florida |website=englandfootball.com |publisher=[[The Football Association]] |date=23 May 2026}}</ref> 

Ngumoha made his debut for the senior England team as a second half substitute during the 1–0 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] victory against [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] on 6 June 2026 at [[Raymond James Stadium]] in [[Tampa]].<ref>{{cite web |title=England vs. New Zealand 1–0: Summary |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/match/england-j9N9ZNFA/new-zealand-rLctHkpU/?mid=hpJGkndD |access-date=6 June 2026 |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group}}</ref> Upon doing so, Ngumoha became the fifth youngest England debutant and the nation's 1,300th senior international.<ref>{{cite web |title=England men's youngest debutants: The top 10 |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2026/Jun/06/England-men-youngest-debutants-20260606|website=englandfootball.com |publisher=[[The Football Association]] |date=7 June 2026}}</ref> He received the Player of the Match Award for his performance.<ref>{{cite web|website=Liverpool FC|date=7 June 2026|access-date=7 June 2026|title=Internationals: Rio Ngumoha and Keyrol Figueroa make senior debuts|last=Shaw|first=Chris|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/internationals-rio-ngumoha-and-keyrol-figueroa-make-senior-debuts|archive-date=7 June 2026|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260607160407/https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/internationals-rio-ngumoha-and-keyrol-figueroa-make-senior-debuts}}</ref>

== Style of play ==
Described as a “skillful” and “creative forward" Ngumoha was included in ''[[The Guardian]]''’s 'Next Generation 2024: 20 of the best talents at Premier League clubs' series.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2024/oct/14/next-generation-2024-20-of-the-best-talents-at-premier-league-clubs|title=Next Generation 2024: 20 of the best talents at Premier League clubs|first1=Marcus|last1=Christenson|first2=Steven|last2=Bloor|first3=Garry|last3=Blight|website=The Guardian|date=14 October 2024|accessdate=14 October 2024}}</ref>

